text.tspan: STEP ONE : MEASURE
utrition and metabolism
Nutrition is the single most important part of your program. The modern Western diet that includes sugary proinfammatory
foods has resulted in the sharp rise of Cardio-Metabolic Disease. Eternity recommends anti-infammatory fresh and natural
foods that mimic the diets of our ancestors (the Paleolithic diet) to control this.
Body fat
Weight alone does not tell you about the metabolic health of your
body. Carrying too much body fat can increase your risk of developing serious
cardiometabolic disease and cancer.
HbA1C
refects the average amount of sugar in your blood over 3 months.
It shows how well you are controlling your diet and refects the degree of
infammation produced by sugar and insulin.
Insulin
helps the cells take up sugar (glucose). Insulin also stimulates the
production and storage of triglycerides and proteins. The most important reason
for measuring the blood insulin level is to distinguish between insufcient insulin
or poor use of insulin (insulin resistance).
Triglycerides
when you eat, your body converts any calories it doesnt need to
use right away into triglycerides. High TG are directly related to high blood sugar
and are 6 times more likely to predict heart disease.
Waist circumference
Excess abdominal fat is a risk factor for developing heart
disease, stroke and diabetes. It is a key marker for the diagnosis of metabolic
syndrome which afects more than 20% of the US population.
HDL-cholesterol H
is for healthy cholesterol - the higher it gets, the greater
your capacity to remove cholesterol and prevent dangerous blockages. Low HDL
is an independent risk for heart disease.
LDL-cholesterol L
is for lousy cholesterol - contains 3 components, LDL (real)
Lp (a) and IDL. Treatment strategy will vary based on these 3 components.
FBS
is your blood sugar level after an 8 hour long fast. A level from 95-125
indicates prediabetes while a level above 125 on 2 separate occasions indicates
diabetes.
Adiponectin
High blood levels of adiponectin are associated with a reduced
risk of heart attack. Low levels of adiponectin are found in people who are obese,
diabetic and those with heart disease.
Leptin
is a hormone that assists in regulating both appetite and metabolism.
Leptin levels are generally proportional to body fat, as leptin is released by fat
cells. Obese people tend to eat more despite high leptin levels that the brain
ignores (leptin resistance).
Resistin
an increase in fat cells leads to an increase in resistin levels that leads
directly to insulin resistance and diabetes. Like leptin it produces infammation.
